%F A292528 For n > 3, the Mycielskian of a graph for a(n-1) shows that a(n) <= 2*a(n-1) + 1. This can be used to show that a(n) <= 3/4 * 2^n - 1 for n > 1.
%F A292528 a(n) >> n^2 log n. In particular, Davies & Illingworth (Theorem 1) can be used to show that a(n) > k*n^2 log n for any k < 1/2 and large enough n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jan 05 2026
%F A292528 Exoo & Goedgebeur prove that a(n) >= 2n - 2 (p. 2, set g = 4 under even girth) and a(n) >= a(n-1) + 3n/2 - 2 (Lemma 1). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jan 05 2026
%e A292528 The unique graph for a(1) = 1 is a lone vertex.
%e A292528 The unique graph for a(2) = 2 is two vertices connected by an edge.
%e A292528 The unique graph for a(3) = 5 is the cycle graph C_5 (the pentagon).
%e A292528 The unique graph for a(4) = 11 is the Grötzsch graph.
%e A292528 There are 80 graphs for a(5) = 22, see the Jensen & Royle link, the Royle link, and the Chen link.
